<div id="review_3636725864" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3636725864" />
    <a title="T.N. Traynor" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7752646-t-n-traynor"><img alt="T.N. Traynor" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1519303097p2/7752646.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3636725864?book_show_action=true">Mar 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="T.N. Traynor" class="user" itemprop="url" name="T.N. Traynor" href="/user/show/7752646-t-n-traynor">T.N. Traynor</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3636725864" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6087996266380292407"><strong>A small book, with a powerful punch</strong><br/><br/>One Swift Summer is an explosion of emotions, like fireworks full of arrs and oohs, all delicately placed in the peace and calm of a swift-graced garden.<br/>The setting is idyllic, the characters few and the prose unforgettable.<br/>Opening and closing from Emma’s point of view, the rest is a poetical internal monologue that became impossible to put down.<br/>Tom dissects his character over several chats with photographer Emma. She watches life in small squares of still life</span>
  <span id="freeText6087996266380292407" style="display:none"><strong>A small book, with a powerful punch</strong><br /><br />One Swift Summer is an explosion of emotions, like fireworks full of arrs and oohs, all delicately placed in the peace and calm of a swift-graced garden.<br />The setting is idyllic, the characters few and the prose unforgettable.<br />Opening and closing from Emma’s point of view, the rest is a poetical internal monologue that became impossible to put down.<br />Tom dissects his character over several chats with photographer Emma. She watches life in small squares of still life, while he ravishes life with gusto and Technicolor reality. I have a masters in pain, he says, and enough material for 10 Ph.Ds.<br />This is an intelligent affair of minds, where love is real and larger than life.<br />Tom has climbed out of the womb of hatred, he has swam upstream determined and dedicated to finding the exit.<br />Amazingly, he is drawn to the birds that fly over the park’s little coffee shop. Swifts with all their grace and freedom.<br />This is a unique, standalone romance with a difference. At first I was confused by the prose, then all of a sudden I fell into the words and reading became as easy as breathing. I was hooked line and sinker, all I can say is that I sincerely hope that we will receive more books from AK Askew! Highly recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6087996266380292407" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


